A '''chemosterilant''' is a [[chemical compound]] that causes reproductive [[infertility|sterility]] in an organism. They may be used to control [[Pest (animal)|pest]] populations by sterilizing [[male]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The toxicology of chemosterilants|journal=Bulletin of the World Health Organization|volume=31|pages=721–36|pmid=14278008|pmc=2555129|year=1964|author1=HAYES WJ Jr}}</ref> More technically, a chemosterilant is any chemical compound used to control economically destructive or disease-causing pests (usually insects) by causing temporary or permanent sterility of one or both of the sexes or preventing maturation of the young to a sexually functional adult stage.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Chemosterilants for Control of Insects and Insect Vectors of Disease|journal=Chimia International Journal for Chemistry|volume=70|issue=10|pages=715–720|doi=10.2533/chimia.2016.715|pmid=27779930|pmc=5108522|year=2016|last1=Baxter|first1=Richard H. G}}</ref>
The mating of sterilized insects with fertile insects produces no offspring, and if the number of sterile insects is kept constant, the percentage of sterile insects will increase, and fewer young will be produced in each successive generation. Chemosterilants should be applied in the larval or pupal stage of the insect to give rise to sterile adults or in the newly emerged adults before they become sexually mature.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/109047/chemosterilant chemosterilant]</ref>
Two types of chemosterilants are commonly used: *[[Antimetabolites]] resemble a substance that the cell or tissue needs that the organism's body mistakes them for a true [[metabolite]] and tries to incorporate them in its normal building processes. The fit of the chemical is not exactly right and the metabolic process comes to a halt. *[[Alkylating agents]] are a group of chemicals that act on [[chromosomes]]. These chemicals are extremely reactive, capable of intense cell destruction, damage to chromosomes and production of mutations.<ref>Carson, Rachel (2002) [1st. Pub. Houghton Mifflin, 1962]. ''Silent Spring''. Mariner Books. {{ISBN|0-618-24906-0}}</ref>
