The '''Grimsel Tunnel''' ({{lang-de|Grimseltunnel}}) is a proposed {{convert|8.3|km|mi|adj=on}} tunnel for power transmission and [[rail transport in Switzerland]].  {{As of|2016}} it was planned to run under the [[Grimsel Pass]] and link the [[Zentralbahn]] at the north end with the [[Matterhorn Gotthard Bahn]] at the south, with planned opening in approximately 2025.<ref name="rg-20160205"/>  The [[Canton of Bern]], [[Canton of Valais]], and [[Swissgrid]] unveiled their joint plans on 4 February 2016.<ref name="rg-20160205"/>

The tunnel is proposed to carry a single-track [[metre gauge railway]] and [[railway electrification system]].<ref name="rg-20160205">{{cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/infrastructure/single-view/view/cantons-back-grimsel-tunnel-between-metre-gauge-networks.html|title=Cantons back Grimsel Tunnel to link metre gauge networks|work=Railway Gazette|date=5 February 2016}}</ref>  The total length of the new '''Grimsel Line''' ({{lang-de|Grimselbahn}}) route containing the tunnel would be {{convert|22|km|mi}}.<ref name="green-20160204"/>  It would link two groups of existing railway lines constructed to one-metre [[track gauge in Switzerland]], forming a contiguous route of {{convert|844|km|mi}}.<ref name="green-20160204"/>
The power transmission cables would run at 380kV and replace [[Swissgrid]]'s existing [[overhead power line]],<ref name="rg-20160205"/> and allow the removal of the 121 [[electricity pylon]]s that had been in place for sixty years.<ref name="srf-20160204"/>

The intended railway route would continue from the [[Brünig railway line]] at [[Meiringen railway station]], via the [[Meiringen–Innertkirchen railway]], to a stop at [[Innertkirchen]], then via new stations at [[Guttannen]] and [[Handegg]] (''{{lang|de|Handeck}}'') to [[Oberwald railway station]] for continuation via the [[Furka Base Tunnel]].  Travel time between Meiringen and Oberwald would be approximately 38 minutes—a reduction of three hours.<ref name="hunkeler-20160204">{{cite news|url=http://www.derbund.ch/bern/region/bern-und-wallis-moechten-schmalspurbahn-durch-die-grimsel/story/30779391|title=In 38 Minuten von Meiringen nach Oberwald|work=Der Bund|first=Michael|last=Hunkeler|date=4 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016|language=de}}</ref>

A company called {{lang|de|Grimselbahn AG}} was founded by the promoters, with Peter Teuscher as its chair person.<ref name="schneeberger-20160204">{{cite news|url=http://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/bahn-und-starkstrom-durch-die-grimsel-1.18689503|title=in Tunnel für Strom und Schiene|work=Neue Zürcher Zeitung|first=Paul|last=Schneeberger|date=4 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016|language=de}}</ref>

In 2016 the estimated cost was 580-million Swiss Francs.<ref name="green-20160204"/> The split cost of 290-million Swiss Francs each for railway and power transmission usage would less than the individual estimated costs of 490-million Swiss Francs for a power-only tunnel or 430-million Swiss Francs for a rail-only tunnel.<ref name="srf-20160204">{{cite news|url=http://www.srf.ch/news/regional/bern-freiburg-wallis/neuer-grimsel-tunnel-zwischen-berner-oberland-und-wallis|title=Neuer Grimsel-Tunnel zwischen Berner Oberland und Wallis|work=SRF|date=4 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016|language=de}}</ref>
The tunnel route had first been proposed in 1860.<ref name="green-20160204">{{cite news|url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/europe/swiss-cantons-reveal-grimsel-pass-railway-plan.html|title=Swiss cantons reveal Grimsel Pass railway plan|work=International Railway Journal|first=Anitra|last=Green|date=4 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>

