'''Heat cost allocators''' are devices attached to individual [[radiator]]s in buildings that measure the total heat output of the individual radiator. Heat cost allocators can be either electronic, where one or two electronic thermosensors<ref>http://www.qundis.com/products/heat-cost-allocators</ref> and a [[microcontroller]] are used to calculate the heat consumption of radiator by the temperature difference between the radiator and the air in room,<ref name= techem>{{cite web|title=Techem: Techem|url=http://www.techem.com/English/products-and-services/measuring-and-billing/meter-reading-and-devices/Heat_Cost/Radio_Heat/
|publisher=Techem}}</ref><ref name=brunatafutura>{{cite web|title=Brunata: Brunata Futura+|url=http://brunata.bg/en/products/allocators/brunata-futura/|publisher=Brunata|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425150627/http://brunata.bg/en/products/allocators/brunata-futura/|archivedate=2012-04-25|df=}}</ref> or evaporative, where a special, calibrated [[liquid]] in a capillary tube records the total heat absorbed from the air (for which an average allowance is made) in addition to that output by the radiator.<ref name=rmk87>{{cite web|title=Brunata: RMK87|url=http://brunata.bg/en/products/allocators/rmk87/|publisher=Brunata|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425151036/http://brunata.bg/en/products/allocators/rmk87/|archivedate=2012-04-25|df=}}</ref>

