A '''human-electric hybrid vehicle''' is a [[hybrid vehicle]], or more specifically a hybrid [[human-powered transport|human powered vehicle]], whose [[hybrid vehicle drivetrain|drivetrain]] consists of a human being and an [[electric motor]]/[[Electrical generator|generator]] (and one or more electricity-storage device(s) such as a [[Battery (electricity)|battery(ies)]] or [[ultracapacitor|ultracapacitor(s)]]). Some vehicles are able to operate off both human power and be plugged in to operate on battery power.<ref>Human-electric hybrid car expected next year (w/ Video); Lin Edwards; August 17, 2010; http://www.physorg.com/news201243600.html</ref>

It  can have characteristics of a [[bicycle]],<ref>High performance electric-human hybrid bicycle; Mike Hanlon; April 30, 2006; http://www.gizmag.com/go/5683/</ref> [[velomobile]] or other lightweight human operated vehicles <ref>'HUMAN-ELECTRIC' HYBRID CAR GOES 30 MPH UPHILL; Alyssa Danigelis; Sat Aug 14, 2010; http://news.discovery.com/autos/human-electric-hybrid-car-goes-30-mph-uphill.html</ref> with the addition of faster [[acceleration]] and [[regenerative braking]], allowing a higher average [[velocity]], especially in hilly terrain.<ref>http://www.gadgettastic.com/2008/01/22/personal-transportation-concept/</ref>

[[Image:Inside1998TwikeActive.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Interior of a 1998 [[Twike]] HEHV]]

Some vehicles have a clutch and three or more wheels, allowing the operator to continue pedalling and charge up the electricity-storage device during traffic stops.

