'''J. Horace McFarland''' (1859–1948) from [[McAlisterville, Pennsylvania]] was a leading proponent of the "[[City Beautiful Movement]]" in the United States.

==Life==
McFarland was the son of [[Union Army|Union]] [[American Civil War|Civil War]] colonel [[George F. McFarland]]. He lived and worked most of his adult life in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]], residing at an estate he named Breeze Hill in the Bellevue Park area of the city. At the estate, McFarland established gardens that featured numerous trees, vegetables, and, most prominently, roses. Photos of his famous gardens reside in the Smithsonian institution. McFarland served as president of the [[American Civic Association]] (ACA) from 1904 to 1924 and the American Rose Society. McFarland and the ACA were a major force promoting civic improvement, environmental [[Conservation (ethic)|conservation]], and beautification in the United States.<ref>Chambliss, Julian C. "Perfecting Space: J. Horace McFarland and the American Civic Association." Pennsylvania History: A Journal of Mid-Atlantic Studies 77, no. 4 (2010): 486-497.</ref> McFarland helped organize the defense of [[Niagara Falls]] from development efforts by power companies, worked to protect [[Yosemite National Park]] with the famous environmental preservationist [[John Muir]], who has been hailed as the father of the [[National Park Service]].<ref>[http://www.aapra.org/Pugsley/McFarlandJHorace.html J. Horace McFarland, Cornelius Amory Pugsley Gold Medal Award, 1937] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010004440/http://www.aapra.org/Pugsley/McFarlandJHorace.html |date=2013-10-10 }} American Academy of Park and Recreation Administration, (Accessed January 10, 2012)</ref>

He is remembered for a statement at the first [[Conference of Governors]] held at the White House, Washington D.C., in 1908:

{{quote|It is the love of country that has lighted and that keeps glowing the holy fire of patriotism.<ref>Address by J. Horace McFarland, [https://books.google.com/books?id=mMPZG4HNAqEC&pg=PA153& Proceedings of a conference of Governors in the White House, Washington, D.C., May 13-15, 1908]. (Accessed January 8, 2012)</ref>}}

His papers are held at the Pennsylvania State Archives.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manuscript Group 85 J. HORACE McFARLAND PAPERS|url=http://www.phmc.state.pa.us/bah/dam/mg/mg85.htm|publisher=Pannsylvania State Archives|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>

